<h3 id="generate-the-plot-of-ph-vs-log-frac-base--acid-">Generate the plot of pH vs. \(\log \frac{ [base] }{ [acid] }\)</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Fit the data to a line (i.e. trendline).</li>
  <li>Calculate the slope (3 sig. figs required) using <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">=SLOPE()</code> function in Excel.</li>
  <li>Calculate the intercept (3 sig. figs required) using <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">=INTERCEPT()</code> function in Excel.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="generate-the-plot-ph-vs-the-logarithm-of-the-dilution-factor">Generate the plot pH vs. the logarithm of the dilution factor</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Generate a single scatter plot of pH vs. the logarithm of the dilution factor (1, 10, 100) for each buffer component using Excel.</li>
  <li>Both data sets should be presented on the same plot.</li>
  <li>Do not fit the data to a trendline.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="assignment">Assignment</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Watch pH meter calibration video</li>
  <li>Watch the videos, pass the postlab quiz, and download your data set for Experiment 6</li>
  <li>Analyze the data in Excel</li>
  <li>Submit your partial lab report in a PDF file and all calculations in an Excel file.</li>
  <li>You should review the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Lab Report Guidelines</code>, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Sample General Chemistry Lab Report</code>, and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Appendix E</code> on D2L while writing to ensure that your drafts are correctly formatted.</li>
</ul>

